import numpy as np

def concatenate_and_unique(arr1, arr2):
    concatenated_arr = np.concatenate((arr1, arr2))
    unique_elements = np.unique(concatenated_arr)
    return len(unique_elements)
\end{code}

`concatenated_arr = np.concatenate((arr1, arr2))`

will concatinate the arrays and

`unique_elements = np.unique(concatenated_arr)`

will return a set of the concatenated array

and the final `return len(unique_elements)` will return the length of the set

so when we run the code with an input:

\begin{code}
input = [1,2,3,4,5]
output = concatenate_and_unique(input, input)
\end{code}

output will be equal to 5
